<td valign="top" class="postbody">
<hr />
I ran over to my local (less than a half-mile away) old cemetery today for the first time in a couple of years - there has been a big improvements in maintenance since the Township took a role in protecting it!
<br />

<br />
It's the Eversole Run (Freshwater) Cemetery, located at  coordinates N40 10.815 W83 09.706, 500 feet West of Concord Road and about 0.3 miles North of the intersection with Cook Road in Delaware County. This is about 1.5 miles North of Muirfield Village / Dublin. 
<br />

<br />
It's entry is well marked, with big yellow signs and some flags. The cemetery is open 9 to 5, and only foot traffic is permitted from the road. The drive leading back to the cemetery is shared with a house built nearby: don't block the driveway by parking there!
<br />

<br />
There is safe parking about 200 feet South of the driveway along the West side of Concord Road: I checked it out, and it's solid even when wet. There is little traffic on Concord Road. (I parked on the East side of the road, in a gravelled access drive the farmer uses to move his tractor to the field. It's big enough for one car).
<br />

<br />
With the exception of a single stone dated 1962, everything is dated pre-1916. The majority of the readable stones are in the range 1841 to 1880. Some of the stones from the mid-1800s are in remarkably good shape, although there are many broken and worn-to-unreadability stones as well.  
<br />

<br />
I used to visit this cemetery 15+ years ago, before it was marked at the road, when there was just a poorly-delineated footpath, and while it was used primarily by local teens having drinking parties. I used to carry out litter (mostly beer cans) every time I visited, and stood up some toppled stones as well. 
<br />

<br />
At that time, I had *no* idea it was as large as it is! Most of the stones were fallen and/or hidden by overgrowth, but the Township maintenance has made clear the boundaries of the graves and restored a sense of order. A house built nearby has undoubtedly played a big role in ending the vandalism, and provided a nice gravel drive for access most of the way back. It could be a tad muddy over the last 50-100 feet to the old entry gate when the temperatures go up. 
<br />

<br />
My beloved Nikon E5700 digital camera has developed a CCD problem (sob!), so the photos I took were substandard. 
<br />

<br />
Coordinates:
<br />
  Cemetery:      N40 10.815   W83 09.706
<br />
  Entry at road: N40 10.813   W83 09.585
<br />
  Parking:         N40 10.789   W83 09.575</td>
</tr>
